{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585806"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:18:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:18:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15017"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15017"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.24,0.07,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52310"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics work through various mechanisms to kill or inhibit the growth of bacteria. Some specifically target DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotics directly inhibits bacterial DNA replication enzymes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Quinolones","Rifampicin","Sulfonamides","Trimethoprim","Metronidazole"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuinolones\u003C/strong\u003E work by directly inhibiting DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV enzymes, which are essential for bacterial DNA replication. This prevents DNA synthesis and leads to bacterial cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options work through different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifampicin\u003C/strong\u003E inhibits bacterial RNA polymerase, interfering with RNA synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESulfonamides\u003C/strong\u003E block para-aminobenzoic acid incorporation into folic acid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E inhibits dihydrofolate reductase in the folate synthesis pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is reduced to toxic metabolites that damage bacterial DNA, rather than directly inhibiting replication enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile several antibiotics ultimately affect DNA synthesis, only quinolones directly target the DNA replication machinery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Quinolones inhibit bacterial DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV enzymes, which are essential for DNA replication","Rifampicin works by inhibiting bacterial RNA polymerase","Sulfonamides and trimethoprim block different steps in the folate synthesis pathway","Metronidazole is converted to toxic metabolites that damage bacterial DNA"],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Pham TDM, Ziora ZM, Blaskovich MAT. Quinolone antibiotics. Medchemcomm. 2019 Jun 28;10(10):1719-1739. doi: 10.1039/c9md00120d. PMID: 31803393; PMCID: PMC6836748."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52310"